aa(lp321
VI want to end with a few words from my late father
p322
aVthat he spoke at my twin brother's wedding.
p323
aVHere's a picture of us.
p324
aVMy dad was a psychologist like me,
p325
aVbut his real love and his real passion was cinema,
p326
aVlike my brother.
p327
aVAnd so he wrote a speech for my brother's wedding
p328
aVabout the roles we play in the human comedy.
p329
aa(lp330
VAnd he said, "The lighter your touch,
p331
aVthe better you become at improving and enriching your performance.
p332
aVThose who embrace their roles and work to improve their performance
p333
aVgrow, change and expand the self.
p334
aVPlay it well,
p335
aVand your days will be mostly joyful."
p336
aa(lp337
VWhat my dad was saying
p338
aVis that we've all been assigned ranges and roles in this world.
p339
aVBut he was also saying the essence of this talk:
p340
aVthose roles and ranges are constantly expanding and evolving.
p341
aa(lp342
VSo when a scene calls for it,
p343
aVbe a ferocious mama bear
p344
aVand a humble advice seeker.
p345
aVHave excellent evidence and strong allies.
p346
aVBe a passionate perspective taker.
p347
aVAnd if you use those tools \u2014
p348
aVand each and every one of you can use these tools \u2014
p349
aVyou will expand your range of acceptable behavior,
p350
aVand your days will be mostly joyful.
